No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a motion to abolish the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was sentenced as part of an amendment to the criminal code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-Prime Minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the motion to reduce penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for signing an allegedly harmful deal with Russia to buy natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicts is to be heard in court.
Timoshenko himself describes the verdict as the regime&#39;s political revenge, and the trial also raised suspicions in the West that the court was biased.
The motion to remove Section 365 from the penal code, on the basis of which the ex-Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its acceptance.
