An obese child&#39;s menu: He doesn&#39;t eat breakfast and eats sausage for supper
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have a problem with being overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which a person grows up and the examples that surround him are for the healthy development of a person.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half as common as in families with children of normal weight.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had fries for supper the day before the awareness campaign under the motto &quot;Obesity is no coincidence&quot;.
In families with fat children, sport is not one of the favorite pastimes either, but this also applies to the majority of today&#39;s schoolchildren - only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, and nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic were interviewed.
This was the second year of the &quot;Adiposity is no coincidence&quot; campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the Unilever company.
More than 12,000 students from the 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project so far.
Unhealthy food and a lack of exercise in the family are decisive factors that are responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of children who are overweight or even obese.
&quot;Only half of the children surveyed said, for example, that they eat five times a day in the form of breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-lunch-evening-dinner - one of the main requirements for a healthy diet,&quot; reads one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relatively small things, such as the family&#39;s regular breakfast time, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of schoolchildren&#39;s families have breakfast.
And - in most families everyone eats breakfast alone.
The worst thing was the finding that every tenth family does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test revealed, among other things, that unhealthy fries are eaten much more often in the families of overweight children.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed play sports, less than half of their parents do so - namely only 15 percent.
Put together your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compose their own menu based on appetite and opinion from the options offered.
&quot;What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of healthy eating.
Among her favorite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and of course desserts.
&quot;The great popularity of sweet lemonades is particularly alarming,&quot; the final report of this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, pasta just won ahead of poultry.
The children didn&#39;t like legumes at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes for lunch was also very low.
return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
&#39;In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after completing the educational lecture &#39;Obesity is not an accident&#39;, in many cases there was a clear shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating,&#39; the project&#39;s findings state.
This was evident, for example, with the sweet sodas, where many children began to give preference to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also ticked poultry or fish as the main dish of the day much more often and were willing to eat fewer dumplings or sweet foods.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article on how stylists learn, I bitched that it was a bit too much stuff to start with.
I had no idea what was to come.
Lectures by three professionals from the industry, the clothing of problematic figures and a seminar on how things work &quot;on the pitch&quot;.
It&#39;s about to get worse.
As the exam approaches, we have more information and practical tasks ahead of us.
But even if the course takes place every Saturday and Sunday, it is still fully booked.
This time we debated with director Alena (not a single man is taking part in the course) how to dress a woman who does not have an ideally proportioned figure.
And most of us are, after all.
Some have a neck that is too short, others have a too boyish figure without proper curves and still others are chubby.
It is up to the stylist to visually conceal broad shoulders, lengthen the neck or conjure up the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a type of woman like Jennifer Lopez - big breasts, wide hips and small waist - in a pretty and form-fitting way without being overly provocative.
For example, if the difference between waist and hips is so big that the skirt or pants really don&#39;t fit, you should have at least one piece made to measure.
You certainly won&#39;t regret it, because well-fitting clothes are simply priceless.
A tailored skirt like this makes you feel a lot better than a ready-made skirt that keeps riding up and down, sticking out at the waist, etc.
Boyish figures, on the other hand, can afford to wear clothing with pleats, puffs, appliqués, embroidery, or ruffles.
With so much information and body types, I&#39;m glad I have a week to think it all through.
And yet I&#39;m afraid that given the homework I&#39;ve been given, it&#39;s almost impossible to do.
Each of the course participants was assigned a celebrity for whom they should think of suitable outfits - daywear and evening wear.
In doing so, we should take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the given star and its body type.
I&#39;m supposed to &quot;dress&quot; Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria&#39;s Secret campaign.
Inside I&#39;m cheering because for me personally it&#39;s a lot better than wearing, for example, Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who seems to have put on a hundred pounds lately (okay, that&#39;s a bit of an exaggeration), or even them young Selena Gomez.
We should cut out the items of clothing from magazines or look for them on the Internet, print them out and then edit them graphically.
In the &quot;moodboard&quot;, as the whole result is called, our very personal style and our relationship to the graphic design should then be expressed.
Because it is very important to also think about the graphic side of the styling.
The stylist not only dresses the models physically, but also designs the so-called product pages in the journals (according to specific specifications, for example trendy handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about it.
But that&#39;s only on Sunday.
This means that a stylist must have a good overall view.
Filled with information about body types, the Saturday lecture was spiced up by three visitors from the industry:
by stylist Jan Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is illusion and that a stylist should be able to take advantage of it.
And a skilled stylist can work with a single piece of clothing in many different ways.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat over jeans as usual, like a t-shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on the naked body, put on heels and wear it as a dress.
It is enough to roll up the sleeves or the collar and the whole look looks completely different.
&quot;Play with it,&quot; he insisted.
But the advice I found most convenient was this: &quot;First, you must know the rules perfectly.&quot;
&quot;Only then can you hurt them,&quot; said Jakub.
I&#39;m finally realizing why we have to learn all these tenets of what goes with what and why, even though fashion journals often show very different things.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared many more variations of clothing than he actually photographs.
So for a fashion story with ten pages (read ten outfits) you have to be prepared to style at least fifteen.
And also that the clothing in the photo sometimes looks completely different in combination with other accessories than in reality.
So you have to take all this into account when designing the outfit.
Jan Pokorný also confirmed to us that image and style sometimes account for half of the success.
All you have to do is look at Madonna, a not-so-brilliant singer whose image and marketing have turned her into a world star.
In the Czech Republic, people tend to be more reserved about the services of a stylist.
Even well-known personalities often consider this to be a waste of money (the main thing is that I bring something, how I look while doing it is secondary).
And if someone does let us style them, then we should reckon with the fact that he or she is very likely to force us into a completely different (smaller) size than he or she actually needs.
Then all you have to do is google it to find out with certainty that the tabloids are writing that the celebrity in question has gained or lost weight again, etc.
Jan and Mario urged us on Sunday not to think that a stylist only needs to focus on the fashion and then &quot;assemble&quot; the outfit.
Above all, his work requires him to communicate with the people he styles and he needs to be a shrewd psychologist.
Assess people without ingratiating yourself and stand by your opinion.
&quot;If some manager calls us to go through her closet and add nice pieces to it, we can&#39;t just clean out her whole closet and say - my God, that&#39;s horrible.&quot;
&quot;You have to find at least some commendable things to recommend what to wear with,&quot; says Mario.
He also showed us very specifically what a so-called &quot;place bag&quot; must contain.
So a bag that you button up at the waist and in which you carry all the necessary properties with you.
In addition to such obvious things as scissors, a hair-removing roller or safety pins, it also contains such utensils as a nylon thread (this helps the stylist when photographing products such as handbags or hats), special clips used to gather clothes at the back , if it&#39;s too big (pins or other clips are forbidden, so that the fabric doesn&#39;t get damaged) and of course sewing kit.
So that we don&#39;t just have to listen, but can also try out something practical, we learned how to properly glue shoes underneath.
Even when taking photos in the studio, where the floor is level, you can damage the sole of a shoe, let alone the one outside.
Us o glued and glued we...
You can&#39;t even touch the shoes with the scissors to avoid damaging them.
So you have to be really clever.
Mario delighted me by praising my &quot;creation&quot; without qualification.
That skill isn&#39;t exactly my forte.
All of this was just a fraction of what we heard on the second weekend continuation course.
One thing has now become clear to me - dedicating yourself to styling at a professional level is not child&#39;s play.
V Need for Speed: &quot;The Run&quot; - the illegal race across America
review
The originally carefree trip turns into a routine trip for the early shift due to a series of completely avoidable, amateurish mistakes.
It was possible to fulfill the ambitions for the most part, but what&#39;s the point if obviously nobody wanted to do a bit more.
Even before it hit the counters, the new installment, subtitled &quot;The Run,&quot; raised high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the long-established &quot;Need for Speed&quot; game series into a new dimension, and in the playable demonstration examples he actually didn&#39;t seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the fitted passages where the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are already used to with NFS, in the end a lot is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they&#39;re pretty decent arcade races, but overall the game is marred by some unnecessary bugs that have been present in this series for more or less a couple of years.
So these are actually no longer errors, but rather signs of an incomprehensibly incomprehensible laziness on the part of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
First you are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, i.e. on the west coast, you get behind the wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race will be held on a different route and that individual stages will take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don&#39;t get the impression for a moment that the game offers the same thing over and over again.
Some of the environments are also extremely nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing earth shattering.
But driving through the desert, through an autumnal landscape or high up through a snow-covered landscape is visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, atypical elements bring a bit of variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that severely reduces visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be extremely careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
Incidentally, the individual races are built in quite well one after the other.
Only a few, but enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (basically a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against a stopwatch), then another personal duel with a single opponent awaits you.
And on top of that, the police get involved, who want to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the wagon.
It&#39;s more about certain interactive animations where Jack is running away from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (actually only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage of the matter, because at least this element has no chance of becoming boring - in the context of the above, it is one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That means, from today&#39;s point of view, it doesn&#39;t uproot any trees, but on the other hand you couldn&#39;t say it&#39;s bad.
If you&#39;re looking for realistic simulations, you&#39;ll have to look elsewhere.
But for action-packed racing, the driving model here still does it quite well, although you could find better ones among the competition.
Until then everything is fine.
Real problems only appear after a certain time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK
It&#39;s hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you don&#39;t have any idea how the car behaves practically before hitting any object, then obviously everything isn&#39;t right.
Typical example: when overtaking or driving past oncoming cars, you only &quot;grab&quot; the other car slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you skid and do wild pirouettes.
Or does the car go straight to the scrap heap.
Thanks to the restart system, that doesn&#39;t matter, but it&#39;s always annoying.
The restarts are solved like this: if you have a total loss or land far off the track, the game throws you back to the last clue on the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you&#39;ve exhausted them, everything starts all over again.
So the restarts are more of a tool in case something goes wrong, but it&#39;s better not to rely on them.
But sometimes even a restart doesn&#39;t help, so nothing else helps than learning the critical section from your head.
What is extremely unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to drive through some corners in a very specific way, otherwise you just don&#39;t fit through.
Elsewhere, at the appropriate place, you always come across &quot;civilian&quot; cars in the same configuration, regardless of whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the opponent in front of you can easily pass two oncoming cars, but by the time you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to avoid them or brake.
And it doesn&#39;t matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that that situation is always right under your nose.
The opponents have other advantages.
There are a few spots throughout the game where you get overtaken by the same opponent in the same place, again regardless of the timing.
The craziest thing is at the end of the game on the long bridge that you cross in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to overtake you come hell or high water here.
And if he&#39;s in front of you, then of course he blocks your view, so that you start by driving your own car into clumps a few times.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly spoils the fun of the game.
And that&#39;s a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining overall and sometimes so action-packed that you almost don&#39;t know where your head is anymore.
And in principle it doesn&#39;t matter what is &quot;to blame&quot; - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in such a way that there is no chance of boredom, or something completely different...
Changing cars during the races is also an unusual idea.
You shouldn&#39;t overlook the petrol stations along the route, because this is where you can change cars, although in most cases the car you have is sufficient.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are well suited for urban areas, powerful American sedans for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example on mountain serpentines.
The task mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations that are known from the story - go hand in hand with the game story mode.
Here you can win not only medals, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and the story.
In order to advance to the higher driver level, various items must be unlocked: starting from the car, ending with the backgrounds for the profile.
At the same time, this is linked to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares your own achieved results with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
One of other incomprehensible blunders is a situation in the last race of the story.
Here you come by car into a subway tunnel (I don&#39;t care) where you race along the rails in the dark (I don&#39;t care).
On the speedometer you can see numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (I don&#39;t care), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and uncompromisingly crashes you.
In our editorial office, we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout by the game designers or whether the authors think we are that stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that the refresh rate slows down in some exciting moments and sometimes quite dramatically.
However, this applies in particular to accidents with a larger number of participants, where continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as broad a range of young audiences as possible, a soundtrack a lá &quot;something of everyone&quot; was created - but who buys a game like this just for the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game weren&#39;t belittled by the aforementioned totally unnecessary bugs, we could have said with heartfelt conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in years.
But the game looks kinda unfinished.
It&#39;s a blast in its own right, but be prepared for these bugs to stab you in the eye with the force of airport headlights.
Concert of the &quot;Students of the Velvet Revolution&quot; with singing ensembles from Charles University
For the third time now, the Festa Academica festival has combined World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, complete with a musical experience.
During the festival, around twenty professional and university choirs will present themselves.
The main focus of the festival are the two concerts that will take place on November 17th.
&quot;Charles University has a big part in the festival.&quot;
&quot;Among the participants are also the choirs of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies, and the festival committee includes, among others, Rector Václav Hampl,&quot; said the head of the organizing team, Jakub Čaloun.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of professional school choirs, which will take place on November 17 from 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the important Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička &quot;Celebration Jazz Mass&quot;.
In the evenings, in the gala halls of the People&#39;s House in Vinohrady, the concert &quot;Students of the Velvet Revolution&quot; (Studenty sametu) will be held, at which university choirs will also perform, including choirs from Charles University.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music of the highest quality to the public and to encourage creative collaboration between young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The entire event was under the patronage of Bohuslav Svoboda, the Mayor of Prague and Václav Hampl, the Rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place in Prague and Pardubice from November 16th to 20th.
In addition to festival concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happenings, matinees and other events.
Those interested can find detailed information on the festival website www.festaacademica.cz
EU Ambassador Vicenová:
The Czechs have a reputation for negativism and Eurosceptics
&quot;The Lisbon Treaty has noticeably upset the balance between the individual institutions.&quot;
I didn&#39;t expect such a hard war to break out.&quot;
&quot;It will take five or six years for things to settle down and for everyone to get used to their new role,&quot; Milena Vicenová, the Czech ambassador to the European Union, began her lecture at the law faculty quite sharply.
