Nobody wants to forbid us our Ölmützer Quargel
Ms. Vicenová also addressed the agenda by which the European Union lived, lives and intends to live in the near future.
She described the Czech presidency two years ago as a success.
The Czechs mastered the financial crisis and the gas crisis and also hosted the Eastern Partnership Summit.
She described the fall of the government during the presidency as a major negative, which badly damaged the image of the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU currently has its hands full.
In the words of the ambassador, not only was the presidency quite hectic, but also the ensuing crisis, which has not yet been overcome.
And then the EU&#39;s seven-year budget still has to be approved, which makes things much more complicated precisely because of the current economic situation.
Whether it will be a lean and frugal budget, which sectors of the economy will be given priority, which countries will receive more and which less funding - all this is now on the agenda.
The ambassador also recalls her own slogan, with which she came to Brussels: &quot;Understandable about Europe&quot;.
&quot;If there&#39;s something I don&#39;t like, it&#39;s grayish abbreviations, foreign words and technical jargon that nobody understands.
As a citizen, how am I supposed to know whether people in Brussels are really thinking up crooked or round cucumbers and bananas of different sizes, or whether someone actually wants to ban the Quargel.
