Brand Story:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to search for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM&#39;s strategy, it would be the word &quot;longevity&quot;.
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company even though a century has passed since its foundation.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson senior.
He already had the slogan that countless world problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan &quot;Think!&quot; thus became the trademark around which the life of the future giant was to revolve (and at the same time the title of the in-house magazine that IBM began publishing as early as 1935).
This was also the basis of the corporate culture thoroughly prepared by Watsen.
&quot;For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a century because it stayed true to its principles and didn&#39;t shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society throughout our first century.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years,&quot; said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company&#39;s current director, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Sophisticated system
As early as the 1930s, Watson was providing social care for his employees - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people were among the first American employees to have paid vacation, insurance from the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes and a well thought-out reward system for the best innovators and dealers.
IBM&#39;s long-term relationships with its customers are just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant at promoting talent from the start - IBM was one of the first companies in the world to abolish all forms of discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
Also in line with this anti-discrimination strategy is the current plan to replace Palmisan at the helm of IBM next year with a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, previously holding the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been doing so-called online brainstorming sessions, from which many future strategies and innovations have emerged.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, the company employs almost half a million people.
An institution with a good reputation
Her unshakable position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
&quot;From the start, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company,&quot; said The Economist, Harvard Business School professor and author of a book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
&quot;IBM is not a technology company, it&#39;s a company that uses technology to help solve business problems,&quot; added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself points out, there is a difference between just being present in the market and directly shaping it through that presence.
IBM - known in the States as &quot;Big Blue&quot; because of its logo - has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most diverse technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in an incredible range of products - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His best-known inventions include ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes and the floppy disk.
At approximately $220 billion in stock market value (market capitalization), IBM was the second largest technology company this year (right after Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
The look ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today&#39;s customers - unfortunate were, for example, the attempt with the company&#39;s own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr.
&quot;Business is based on moving forward, so don&#39;t get emotionally attached to the past,&quot; says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That&#39;s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and when they don&#39;t work, leaving them again.
In contrast to the competitor Microsoft, who in principle stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising Technologies
Services contribute the most to IBM&#39;s profits, with software and hardware each accounting for one-fifth.
In 1990, hardware was still the strongest with a share of more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has divested $15 billion of low-yielding assets while investing $58 billion in acquisitions of promising technologies.
IBM continues to make these investments after 2008, when the modern financial crisis first hit the world like a storm.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment scope in the middle of the Great Depression.
So far it seems that the IBM company will survive today&#39;s crisis unscathed.
The value of IBM stock has skyrocketed 120 percent since 2008, and the company&#39;s net income continues to grow.
IBM&#39;s corporate slogan is: everything can be changed - except the values.
This is another reason why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also master the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flight
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It only took over the IBM name in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later IBM company was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous time card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the board of directors until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired the head of rival firm Thomas J. Watson to help run the company.
This leader even eclipsed the founders of IBM - the company&#39;s invincible culture and identity is still based on Watson&#39;s ideas today.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the manufacture and sale of all kinds of machines for retail - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson ran the company, he doubled its sales to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to every continent.
Watson was so essential to the company that he was in charge for forty years before being succeeded by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped NASA guide flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and, in 1969, man&#39;s famous flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of the time, came onto the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thereby fully entered the business of consulting and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid off in the last three years is the &quot;Smarter Planet&quot; concept.
It embodies the intention of using technology wisely in areas that have not even been planned before, including improving the situation in transport and city management.
In the commerce sector, IBM recently launched the Smarter Commerce platform, designed to help merchants manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932 IBM founded a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia - as the very first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR operates, among other things, a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague, and it is also home to a world-class, top-class research team working on voice recognition technology.
