Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five licensed state travel agencies in the then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies mainly only sold trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, only a select few were allowed to go to the West.
And so, Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea, and to Hungary to Lake Balaton.
A notable exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries.
If a Czech citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or even the Soviet Union, for example, they needed a so-called letter of invitation, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to put up with huge queues or spend the night in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have &quot;good friends&quot; in the travel agency.
Things hadn&#39;t gone that way for a long time either.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for leaving for the West - was only given to &quot;politically reliable&quot; people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dachas - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday destination of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the obligation to exchange foreign currency in neighboring Western European countries was lifted, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time, the Czechoslovaks simply couldn&#39;t get enough of their trips to the West, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
Czech vacationers, for example, slept in tents in parks when traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money for hotel or boarding house accommodation back then?
A typical feature of Czechs traveling abroad at that time was a trunk packed with canned goods, beer and sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech koruna - after decades, our tourists could finally buy the western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thereby also the average salary increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
After 1997, thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly arrange trips through charter flights, which made air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, already had non-currency payments with all highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of &quot;post-velvet&quot; travel came in 2000, when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand - was operated.
Since then, direct charter planes with Czech passengers have flown to distant, sunny countries every year; this year twelve exotic destinations will be flown to directly from the Czech Republic.
Around 100,000 Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our &quot;post-revolutionary&quot; development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visa requirements for Czech tourists, which definitely put our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than CZK 15,000 per capita on a single vacation including costs at the vacation destination.
The general meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate is imminent.
Czech football has been without a chairman for almost five months and threatens that Ivan Hašek&#39;s successor at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not be known even after Thursday&#39;s extraordinary general meeting in Nymburk.
