Europe&#39;s most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pools in the shape of a UFO, ceremonial pools in Budapest: anyone traveling through Europe can experience their blue miracle - and rest their tired legs in whirlpool baths after a city tour or a hike.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past year and a half, one thing she couldn&#39;t do without was her swimsuit.
Lying on her back on the water, she looked up at the artistically designed domes, she swam towards marble putti waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at the meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bathroom, she immediately jotted it down in her notebook - along with details worth knowing about the construction and history of the building.
Architectural historian Meder explored more than 200 swimming pools in this way - and is now presenting them in her recently published book &quot;Badefreuden&quot;: public swimming pools in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, &quot;hardcore concrete buildings&quot; in the Taunus.
Her &quot;journey to the most extraordinary pools in Central Europe&quot; took her through 13 countries: In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg , Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn&#39;t have much to do with sports, says Meder - it&#39;s just different in the water.
It&#39;s just annoying that swimmers have to put up with blue tiles and the stench of chlorine, while joggers can breathe in the intoxicating scent of spruce forests or listen to the happy chirping of birds in the park.
&quot;One day I asked myself why swimming pools always have to be so ugly,&quot; says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
&quot;So I started collecting beautiful baths.&quot;
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashing in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, indoor swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: &quot;Instead of a floor, bathrooms have a water surface.&quot;
&quot;On the one hand it is transparent, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building.&quot;
Everything doubles optically: high vaults, colorful tiles, diving boards.
The small-format photo book &quot;Badefreuden&quot; provides 190 pages worth knowing about the architectural and cultural history of historic wellness oases - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-rich body of water in a quaint karst cave (Cave Bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath whose pools are filled with alkaline water and housed in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jaszbereny).
On the other hand, many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: While you can see the whole city from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can see the snow-covered Arlberg from the outdoor pool of a pool in St. Anton - and: there is a window in the steam bath , from which you can watch the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most unusual pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, it steams from three bowls that are open at the top, while the mountains of the Ötztal tower into the sky in the background.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Pool collector Meder did not catch the smell of chlorine in every swimming pool.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the Árpád baths in Békescsaba, Hungary, it stinks so strongly of heating oil that you hardly believe you have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline-bicarbonate healing water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a special kind of wellness experience.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing pool in the Czech spa in Luhatschowitz, she found a closed-off area.
The bath, designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has since been closed.
Peering through the weathered windows of the red, white, and yellow Art Nouveau building, Meder saw weeds growing between the tiles.
On the other hand, the deterioration has been counteracted in an enchanting swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This pool has already completed three construction phases; Not only can you discover neo-Romanesque elements dating back to when it was built in 1844, but also an Alhambra-style Moorish hall, added around 1900.
Since it was carefully modernized in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not just because she originally comes from the Black Forest.
&quot;It&#39;s quite an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit,&quot; says Meder.
With such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
agricultural speculation
Deutsche Bank has its commodities business screened
By Christian Teevs
Is Deutsche Bank going out of business with soft commodities?
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE information, Josef Ackermann has commissioned a working group to examine the consequences of speculation for the world&#39;s poor.
In January, the CEO then wants to draw conclusions.
Hamburg -
