Foodwatch tries to keep the pressure on the manager high.
So far, more than 30,000 internet users have taken part in the organization&#39;s campaign.
Bode published the survey on Tuesday, for which the Forsa Institute interviewed 1001 people on November 7th and 8th.
Just eleven percent consider it legitimate that Deutsche Bank offers investments in which food prices are bet on.
Many bank customers would also draw personal consequences if they found out that their bank was involved in such transactions: According to the survey, every second customer would terminate all investments in which money flows into commodity speculation.
43 percent would advise acquaintances against such a bank, 49 percent said they were thinking about closing their account and switching to another institute.
21 house in Vienna
The moved pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural story with ups, downs and a happy ending: The Austrian world exhibition pavilion in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and fell into disrepair.
Now it will be reopened as an exhibition hall.
If people rave about modern post-war architecture, about clear forms, glass halls, bold curves and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwartzer for the Brussels World Exhibition in 1958 is a fitting and famous example .
Back then, Schwacher&#39;s pavilion received the Grand Prix d&#39;Architecture for its light steel and glass construction, which appears to be floating.
The building is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built Austria&#39;s pavilion at the next world exhibition.
He finally became internationally famous in 1973 with his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like annexe in Munich.
His pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the world exhibition in the Swiss Garden near Vienna&#39;s southern railway station, remodeled and opened in 1962 as a museum of the 20th century - it was called the &quot;20er Haus&quot;.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls to hang the art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art found a new home in Vienna.
The building had been empty since 2001 and was gradually falling into disrepair.
The architect Adolf Krischanitz has now rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called &quot;21er Haus&quot; and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the building belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, pushed through the new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, who has a doctorate in art history and had a remarkable career, including in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby&#39;s, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, pushed through the conversion with politicians and monument conservationists, she raised public funds and private sponsorship money and determined the usage.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the implementation.
Not only because he had sensitively remodeled and expanded Joseph Olbrich&#39;s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied under Schwacher at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an &quot;incredibly important place&quot; for him, where he &quot; almost every weekend&quot; had seen the exhibitions.
He knew the original design and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and repurposed.
There were far greater problems with the current conversion: the building was &quot;an energy slingshot,&quot; says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced with special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced and asbestos-filled ceilings have been rehabilitated.
Two basement floors provided space for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides the light, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light-weight tail-pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain and the house is painted in the old reddish-brown anti-rust colour.
And the cinema hall is even exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
&quot;Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and that the monument protection office also liked,&quot; says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion &quot;that came from Brussels,&quot; Krischanitz said recently, a typical &quot;drop-in-the-city thing.&quot;
Such architecture is &quot;always in the wrong place&quot; and still wants to &quot;raise a real awareness&quot;.
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban stroke of luck has occurred: around the Schweizer Garten, the completely newly planned &quot;Hauptbahnhofsquartier&quot; is being built, with office and residential buildings.
And another stroke of luck may yet happen: The 21er Haus could be reinforced by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporäre Kunsthalle and, as has been heard, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss Garden.
