The scandal bank from Lake Zurich
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not based in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt during the financial crisis and has been sliding from one crisis to the next ever since.
Now a German should fix it.
Axel Weber certainly hadn&#39;t thought of it that way.
After his spectacular departure from the top of the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would start an almost equally spectacular new job in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the major Swiss bank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career step.
Axel Weber was publicly delighted, praising Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newly won solidity, and dropping friendly remarks about future colleagues.
&quot;UBS has managed the turnaround&quot;.
&quot;I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel&quot;.
But as early as September it became clear that everything would turn out very differently.
A UBS dealer in London bypassed all of the bank&#39;s security systems and gambled away around 1.7 billion euros.
UBS CEO Oswald Grübel, a banker not only famous in Switzerland, had to go.
Since then, the Chairman of the Board of Directors of UBS has also been considered ailing - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally come?
It has already been announced that Weber may advise the bank from February 2012.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the board of directors in May - not just in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
It will be tough for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, but rather an economics professor and central banker and would certainly have needed an induction period.
In one fell swoop, he then assumes responsibility for the strategy of a bank that has just proven once again that it has long since earned the title of &quot;biggest scandalous bank in Europe.&quot;
On the one hand, UBS is huge - until recently it was the largest wealth manager in the world - and on the other hand it has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, will be spared the once proud Swiss bank.
It started with the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of the secretive and solid, but also savvy Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: She also wanted to be a big hit in investment banking.
In 2007, for example, UBS managed more money from wealthy customers than any other bank in the world, at $1.6 trillion.
And on the other hand, as an investment bank, it had advanced into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later longtime banking professor in Zurich Hans Geiger says: &quot;Back then, I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank.&quot;
&quot;From today&#39;s point of view one asks oneself: How could I be so wrong?&quot;
He was terribly wrong.
In 2007 it became apparent for the first time that something was seriously wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker, resigned surprisingly.
A few months later you could guess why he had left.
The bank&#39;s investment division had gambled away with subprime paper and had to write off billions.
To shoulder that, UBS announced a capital increase of a whopping CHF 13 billion.
She actually found investors for this, albeit ones that some would have turned up their noses at a short time ago: an opaque Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund that was so secretive that you didn&#39;t even find out its name.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008 things got worse.
The bank had to announce new losses in the billions, and Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel, who in 2006 was still the second-best paid member of the Board of Directors in Switzerland, resigned.
The catastrophe followed in October 2008: UBS was on the verge of collapse due to its bad investments during the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought problematic securities from UBS for tens of billions, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a compulsory convertible bond, through which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because they noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it houses such large banks.
After all, UBS&#39;s balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times the size of Switzerland&#39;s economic output (see chart).
&quot;We couldn&#39;t save UBS again,&quot; says bank researcher Geiger.
The second catastrophe followed the first.
Just a few months later, UBS capitulated in the tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who might have evaded taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million - as repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty surcharge.
UBS thus admitted more or less openly that it had helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her asset in the competition for rich customers: the aura of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was never the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the CEO and President of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer funds.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both of its central business areas: in investment banking due to the bad speculations and in asset management due to the help to tax evasion.
And just when things got a little quieter again, just when you thought UBS would get it right again, this unfortunate trader story follows: A single trader gambles away 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it&#39;s becoming obvious that risk management in investment banking is obviously still not working.
&quot;With the Adoboli case, one had to realize that risk control had changed too little,&quot; says Martin Janssen, an economist and finance professor at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The CFO of a large German bank is also certain: &quot;UBS&#39;s problem is that it doesn&#39;t have risk control under control.&quot;
It was precisely the idea of prudence with which the Swiss bankers set out a long time ago to become the guardians of the great fortunes of the world: no great risks, but security for the money - even if the world collapsed beyond the Alpine republic .
The vaults of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unshakable reliability, just like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly fine chocolate.
The UBS headquarters in Zurich still fit the cliché of the dignified Swiss private bank - it&#39;s just a bit bigger.
Even the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich&#39;s Bahnhofstrasse, which leads from the main train station directly to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers like Tiffany&#39;s can be found here between traditional Swiss shops like Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have been based here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
The UBS reception room is entered through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are clad in marble, thick leather armchairs stand in front of them, and next to the bank logo is a large sign indicating the &quot;safe&quot;.
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
However, both major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, eventually suppressed this idea of the Swiss bank - or, as the head of a small Swiss private bank thinks, betrayed it.
He would rather not read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two major banks.
He thinks that UBS has become much too big - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also spread.
The Swiss would no longer have a say there.
&quot;And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons.&quot;
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, first bringing it high profits and then the debacle: no other European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the major Swiss bank.
On October 15, 2008, the catastrophe became visible.
&quot;On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small country of seven million decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation,&quot; writes the author Lukas Hässig in his book &quot;The UBS Crash&quot;.
The politicians approved up to 68 billion francs or around 45 billion euros to save the bank from bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem primarily in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged to form a huge group.
A bank was created that was already too big for little Switzerland when it merged - and it continued to grow.
It helped that the two different predecessor banks of UBS complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on wealth management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers got a lot of cheap money with which to spin a giant wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
&quot;I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,&quot; says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
&quot;Wuffli, the highly intellectual, modest, who knows a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the gut person, who worked his way up from the bank apprenticeship to the very top.&quot;
But in the end Ospel relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a crucial mistake in the end: &quot;He thought his models were reality,&quot; says Geiger.
&quot;This is a tragic case.&quot;
Tragic, maybe.
One thing is clear: exuberance came before the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the management meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: push Goldman Sachs off the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank on earth.
She led the &quot;League Tables&quot;, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of the time.
That&#39;s where UBS wanted to go, to the top.
She had already taken a few steps.
In the foreign exchange business and in stock trading, she played at the top.
Management consultants who were commissioned, however, emphasized a weakness: In the international interest business, in banker&#39;s language &quot;fixed income&quot;, there is a huge gap to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in American mortgage products.
To fill this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that nearly cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund established before it invested in American subprime investments.
It grew into a mighty machine that packaged and passed securities on American mortgage loans—while also retaining risk itself.
Even when other banks were already looking to exit.
&quot;UBS was still buying there in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was in flames,&quot; says banking expert Geiger.
As great as the euphoria, as deep as the fall.
One manager after another had to leave when attempts to clean up proved more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS became an ejection seat and remain shaky to this day.
Anyone who runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He has to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: put an end to investment banking, concentrate on asset management, return to your Swiss roots.
The bank doesn&#39;t want to go that far (yet).
But investment banking is set to shrink sharply, that much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new bank boss Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a temporary solution when the bank surprisingly parted ways with its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has asserted himself: he should permanently manage the business of UBS, the Zurich bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to take the investment bank back to where it was in the mid-1990s.
He is cutting 3,500 jobs.
But that won&#39;t be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
How does she want to make money?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is certainly already asking himself.
So far he has only said publicly that he and his wife will first look for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
