Intelligent crows are spreading throughout cities
In many places, rooks are seen as &quot;problem birds&quot;: But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many communities there are increasing numbers of complaints from residents about the animals&#39; dirt and noise.
A remedy for the &quot;problem birds&quot; is not yet in sight.
Experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian town of Leer that rooks can no longer be gotten out of the cities.
There, experts from all over Germany discussed possible ways out.
They are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the specially protected rookers: the use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing building and the felling of typical nesting trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected.
There are large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs in Soest in Westphalia, in the north-west in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the district made negative headlines.
Critics had described the catching of the animals in bird traps and beating them with clubs as particularly brutal.
&quot;The normal expulsion, the scaring away, brings nothing,&quot; said urban and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Splashing away nests with water or cutting down trees often have undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
&quot;The animals evade, large colonies split up and spread to other places.&quot;
Deterrence is only conceivable as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
&quot;We have to live with them, we can&#39;t get rid of them.&quot;
The problem in the cities cannot be solved without the surrounding area, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
A combination of deterring the animals from sensitive living areas and offering lures to resettle them in other places is conceivable.
&quot;Information boards instead of chainsaws,&quot; the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens, on the other hand, advocated a completely different approach to animals: &quot;After all, we&#39;re best able to face a pimple on our face with confidence.&quot;
In Schleswig-Holstein, Jürgens co-founded the Ascheberg crows educational trail, where signs provide information about the life of the highly intelligent rooks.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of the birds: &quot;There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other.&quot;
The intelligence and dexterity of the animals are legendary: rooks not only use tools to get a treat, they even use tools to make their own tools.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested four rooks to see how far the birds&#39; intelligence reaches.
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to use stones to break down scaffolding in order to get at a moth larva.
Without much training, they single-mindedly recognized what size and shape a stone needs to be in order to collapse the platform.
In a second attempt, the clever crows then had to solve a trickier problem.
The researchers placed a small bucket with a moth larva in a vertical cylinder.
The birds could not reach their prey with their beaks.
However, the researchers had put pieces of wire down for them.
All four animals used this to form a hook, which they then used to fish the bucket out of the tube by the handle.
Three of the four rooks even managed to do this right away.
