Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which determines the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He has written an unusual book, which he not aptly describes as &quot;a work of anti-history&quot;.
It contains only a few big names, important treaties or famous battles. There are hardly any ambassadors, frenzied reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment.
It&#39;s less a book about what happened, he explains, and more &quot;a book about how it was.&quot; It is about &quot;feelings, impressions, experiences and moods&quot;.
&quot;Beauty and Horror&quot; summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people become heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go insane, or die.
Each of these lives flares up like votive candles in a church, some coming in while others go out.
Englund&#39;s book deviates from the usual history books.
It also corrects the notion that World War I was just the devastating trench warfare on the western front.
&quot;Beauty and Horror&quot; wanders over other theaters of war with an expert&#39;s eye: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Beehives fall on the soldiers in this book, one celebrates Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, tsetse flies are an insurmountable problem.
This is a moving book almost from the start.
The war swamps the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of cordite.
Imagine you are a woman at home with her children and hear cannon fire in the distance. Do you stay or do you flee?
Who is coming anyway?
Hardly anyone understands what is happening or why this war is being waged at all.
&quot;Missing facts,&quot; notes Englund, &quot;have been bolstered with hunches, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumours.&quot;
&quot;Beauty and Horror&quot; follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German seaman.
Their stories were mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other previously published material.
Their life stories can be terrifying or poignant, but they are intensely vivid in Englund&#39;s lost-detail collection of small moments.
Many of them are about lack and making do.
In the story of a German schoolgirl, he says: &quot;Replacement, replacement everywhere.&quot;
&quot;Substitute coffee, wrong aluminum, wrong eraser, paper bandages, wooden buttons.&quot;
He tells more about substitute food in Germany.
He describes &quot;meat made from pressed rice and fried in mutton fat (and last served with a false bone made of wood), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato skins, shoes soled with wood.&quot;
There were, he notes, &quot;837 registered food substitutes allowed in the manufacture of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes.&quot;
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American, recognizing his own thirst for savagery, says of the war: &quot;One feels that, after all, this is what men were meant for rather than sitting in an armchair with the evening paper or the bestseller and a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, and to pretend that such a facade signifies civilization and that there is no barbarism behind one&#39;s starched and studded shirt-front.&quot;
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he will probably die and that no one will notice or care.
&quot;When you step away from the idea of sacrificing yourself, you want to think it&#39;s happening in front of an audience,&quot; he writes.
Instead, it&#39;s as horrific as &quot;a condemned man hanged in secret.&quot;
Other observations are about the old Europe falling apart and about new forms of terror.
&quot;The conflict increasingly became an economic contest,&quot; writes Englund, &quot;a war between the factories.&quot;
He captures the arrival of what he calls &quot;a new species in the early century&#39;s bestiary&quot;: &quot;the eloquent and ideologically staunch mass murderer in a tailored suit who butchers while seated behind a desk.&quot;
People behave in unforeseen ways, and there is frivolous behavior as well as heroism.
Englund discusses the soldiers who actively tried to contract an STD from a prostitute to escape front-line service.
&quot;The grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade in gonococcal pus, for soldiers bought and smeared it on their genitals in hopes of getting into the hospital,&quot; he writes.
&quot;Those who were truly distressed would rub it in their eyes, resulting in them being blind for the rest of their lives.&quot;
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Englund&#39;s poetry becomes supple yet unassuming, adapting perfectly to his human task.
In dozens of small scenes, he captures how the war &quot;uniquely unleashed uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.&quot;
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders make them fight.
The best books on WWI tended to be more biased, like Paul Fussell&#39;s Great War and Modern Memory, or novels like Erich Maria Remarque&#39;s Nothing New in the West, than lengthy history books.
Englund&#39;s band joins an unconventional hall of fame.
His book has the most devastating ending I&#39;ve ever read about in non-fiction.
I don&#39;t give it away anymore.
But it&#39;s as if he had snatched that page with the main characters from under our noses in his book and lit it with a match.
