After this summer&#39;s tragedy, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It&#39;s easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
&quot;We found that it wasn&#39;t difficult to get to them,&quot; says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook&#39;s stash of personal data is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers simply have to use the site&#39;s advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographics with scientific rigor -- just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett&#39;s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with Adds, but rather than linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to take a poll asking about their educational level, their attitude towards violence and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave their office.
&quot;It&#39;s a fairly new research method,&quot; says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and resentful of immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, &quot;those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more sane, democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens.&quot;
DEMO&#39;s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a hot new tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends, as seen in &quot;likes,&quot; text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook&#39;s &quot;data supernova&quot; is generating a research boom that has seen the number of scientific papers with this site&#39;s name in the title increase by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that through this site you can study people you wouldn&#39;t normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
&quot;In the past, if you tried to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.&quot;
&quot;They had to inform the party first and they would never have let them in,&quot; says Bartlett.
&quot;Facebook doesn&#39;t do all that - you go straight to them.&quot;
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their binge drinking on Facebook were significantly more likely to have problem drinking than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student when it posts too many status updates.
&quot;You can&#39;t solve a problem if you don&#39;t recognize it,&quot; Dimitri Christakis, Moreno&#39;s co-author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children&#39;s Research Institute in Seattle, told The Washington Post.
&quot;We found a way to identify vulnerable children that would not have been found otherwise.&quot;
Facebook is also constantly tapping into data from its own population.
The site&#39;s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine&#39;s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections and a National Happiness Index (primarily using data only Facebook has access to - digital freedom champions have long known that the site gives its should make a large data repository accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know the page is watching them whether they want it or not. In order to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to reveal your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don&#39;t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, anything goes online.
&quot;I don&#39;t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,&quot; says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, of a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of Studied students on Facebook.
&quot;As for her, it was all about her and her friends.&quot;
Then there is the issue of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it&#39;s impossible to know how much of the information in a user&#39;s profile and post is true.
&quot;What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things,&quot; says Selwyn.
So, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks a clipboard and pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
&quot;There&#39;s no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,&quot; he says.
&quot;Social research needs to look at the social - and a lot of social life still happens offline.&quot;
