7 lessons from the late Steve Jobs interview shown at a theater this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, citing the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But perhaps what Apple fans will find most telling in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted this week ahead of special screenings in major markets, is how well this creative mind understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who avidly tinkered with diagrams - a man who believed many business leaders suffered from &quot;a disease of thinking, &#39;that a really great one Idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there&#39;s a tremendous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product.&quot;
In 1995, Bob Cringely created the TV series &quot;Triumph of the Geeks&quot; about the dawn of the personal computer. And he sat with Jobs for more than an hour during which they had one of those rare in-depth conversations.
At this point, more than 10 years had passed since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple. And he was already hard at work on his new computer company, NeXT, looking forward to widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley&#39;s interview was used in Fachidiot, he says the interview master copies were missing when it was delivered.
It wasn&#39;t until after Job&#39;s death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director&#39;s garage.
This slightly remastered footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film &quot;Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview,&quot; which hits Landmark theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who has a reputation for abhorring lengthy interviews, Jobs appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
During the course of the interview, there are four lengthy pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of contemplation, during which Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts and striving for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs&#39;s perfectionism comes to the fore, when he seems to react impatiently to Cringely&#39;s questions and nudges him to move more quickly on issues or subplots of greater importance.
Recorded before the Pixar, iPod or iPhone era, the Lost Interview seems somehow eerily prescient as Jobs assesses what he thinks other companies are doing right and wrong and sets out his own vision of the future of computing.
It&#39;s one thing to read posthumous tributes to Jobs&#39; career. But seeing Jobs here as the aspiring dreamer on the verge of greatness is something very different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he did all this, he went out and did it.
A quick look at seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
&quot;Throughout my years in business, I always ask, &#39;Why do you do things?&#39; And the answer you always get is, &#39;Oh, that&#39;s just the way it&#39;s done.&#39;
Nobody knows why he does what he does. No one in business really thinks deeply about things.
I have found that.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Amazed at how costs were recorded - most often starting with &quot;standard costs&quot; which were calculated on mere guesswork and then adjusted with &quot;variance&quot; - he developed an automated factory that ensured that the cost of doing business could be pinpointed down to the last detail .
How the Pope was teased:
Jobs tells of the &quot;blue box&quot; he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed you to sneak into the phone company and make long distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs&#39; enthusiasm as he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&amp;T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
&quot;We sent stuff around the world half a dozen times and if you yelled into the phone, it came out a minute later on the phone next door,&quot; Jobs says with a chuckle.
&quot;We were young and we learned that we could build something ourselves that could control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.&quot;
Both of us, we didn&#39;t know much, but being able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don&#39;t think Apple would exist without it.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank he and Wozniak almost pulled when they called the Vatican via Blue Box in the middle of the night and wanted to speak to the Pope while imitating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
With several members of the Catholic hierarchy summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two burst out laughing before the Pope himself got on the phone.
How he fell in love with tech (and, unprepared, called Bill Hewlett):
At age 12, while looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs landed a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
&quot;It had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views of what a company was and how well it treated its employees.&quot;
Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company&#39;s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw &quot;the first desktop computer ever made&quot;.
It was the size of a suitcase, had a small screen with a Braun tube, and I fell in love with it.
I would climb up HP as a teenager and be attached to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Jobs talks several times in the interview about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he was installing some circuit boards, a customer asked him to assemble the whole computer.
Working with a payment deadline of just 30 days, he had to think through both assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had developing a computer mouse:
&quot;I remember making powerful arguments... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer.&quot;
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we could have built for $15. That was incredibly believable.
About Big Companies Slacking:
Long before he resurrected Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their vision and lost control of their stocks.
&quot;Let&#39;s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, so what?&quot;
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it&#39;s people like that] who ultimately run the company and the product that push people out of the decision-making process.
The product genius that led to this monopoly is being eradicated by people who have no concept of good vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This is what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if that could have been Microsoft in the 1990s...
They caught defeat from victory.
About innovation as an art form:
&quot;There&#39;s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... as you develop that great idea, it changes and grows.&quot;
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
You have to do attunements, certain things you can&#39;t do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and put them all together...
Ultimately it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to engage with the best stuff that humans have made and then trying to bring those things together into what you&#39;re making.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn&#39;t for computers, they would be doing amazing things in other areas.
