How to spot a lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy dealing with allegations of sexual harassment from several women. Both sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State officials have been charged with perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, over an open microphone, French President Nikolas Sarkozy claimed to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself circulating denials that were quickly contradicted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign finance violations linked to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who lived to see it forgets the media frenzy unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories of cheating at school and on college exams are common.
There have been instances where teachers have provided their students with exam answers so that they can do well on their own assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies are considered white lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Detecting lies, or &quot;detecting lies,&quot; is a skill that is important for everyone to learn, for both personal and professional reasons.
A far cry from a parlor game such as charades, in which the goal is &quot;Have you!&quot; to shout, deception detection is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities conducting wide-ranging research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don&#39;t always stutter, stammer, blush, or fidget.
However, one should not conclude from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and unmask.
A skilled lie-detector can break through to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the subtle facial expressions, questioning, and timing.
I have spent several years researching the scientific evidence in the vast and ever-expanding field of exposure. And it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us navigate our complex world, especially when one&#39;s job responsibilities involve hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or managing .
Good liars are very good at gauging other people, getting their interest, and controlling their own emotions. And they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell &quot;self-oriented&quot; lies more often than women, whose lies are more &quot;other-oriented&quot;—usually to protect other people&#39;s feelings—that married People lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly &quot;fat lies&quot;).
We also know that when a person is exposed as a wrongdoer, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing that person&#39;s normal behavior.
This is called &quot;baselining&quot;, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the quality of the voice of your subject.
They&#39;d better know when someone usually taps their feet all the time so they don&#39;t unfairly blame them for tapping their feet during a meeting.
Then look out for accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behavior.
Think of these clusters as alarm bells ringing, not evidence of exposure.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet are pointing toward the door or they&#39;re leaning toward the exit, changing their position in a significant way, or exhibiting a &quot;post-interview relaxation,&quot; that deep, relaxing exhale and shift in posture when all the tough questions are over.
Questioners often falsely signal that an interview is over just to look for that post-interview relaxation.
Also pay attention to the language of your test subject.
Scott Peterson&#39;s slip is famous when he used the past tense when claiming his slain wife was still alive, sparking a national search for her.
Deceptive people may also use distancing language: &quot;I have not had a sexual relationship with this woman...Miss Lewinsky&quot; or repeating a tricky question in its entirety.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use &quot;qualifying language&quot; when answering a tricky question: &quot;Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge.&quot;
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual, which often sets off alarm bells.
There is no magic cure for detecting lies, but you can learn skills that will allow detection.
With these skills, everyone can be less likely to fall victim to scammers, both in their personal and professional lives.
