Formation of the new Italian government on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti is meeting the President of Italy tomorrow to present the new government set up to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti is meeting the President of Italy tomorrow to present the new government set up to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
He is expected to unveil a majority technocrat cabinet, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present the results of talks with political parties to form a government to the President.
&quot;I would like to reiterate my absolute confidence in our country&#39;s ability to deal with these difficult times,&quot; the former EU Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not specifically confirm the formation of the government, but his comments indicate that the obstacles have been overcome.
&quot;The framework is now well defined,&quot; he added.
Monti managed to form a government in less than three days, much less time than normal. Meanwhile, Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of the debt to unbearable levels.
The new government, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must pass a tough austerity package demanded by Euro-politicians in order to regain shattered confidence in Italy.
The pressure to hurry on Monti was compounded by volatile market conditions, which resulted in Italy&#39;s 10-year government bonds being charged at 7 percent. This corresponds to the level at which Greece and Ireland felt compelled to apply for the European bailout fund.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industrial association Confindustria, told the press after meeting Monti: &quot;We said we would support this government as much as we could.&quot;
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti&#39;s chances of success were significantly increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi&#39;s PDL party, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
&quot;We believe that Professor Monti&#39;s efforts are destined to produce good results,&quot; said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
Support for the PDL, Italy&#39;s largest party, is essential because so far many of its members have opposed a technocrat-majority government that Monti is forming.
support from Parliament
Monti&#39;s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity measures.
Resisting its efforts or delaying reforms could trigger another devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also exerting pressure, saying that a failure by Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his debates with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as youth and women&#39;s organizations on Monday.
The session is scheduled to conclude Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who launched an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief sigh of relief towards the end of last week when it was announced that Berlusconi would resign, the cost of Italian government bonds has again reached critical limits due to uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
A rescue of Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU rescue package.
Monti said his government must last until the next elections, which are expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms rather than bringing the elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist that it should be made up only of technicians, an indication of their concerns about the procedure imposed by financial market pressures.
Political sources indicate that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the involvement of political figures.
