The quintet included Costa Rica in their 20th anniversary tour
&quot;Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true&quot;
Speaking exclusively to Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament says the band is geared up to play one of their best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
They have been awaited for more than 20 years, but the band assures that a dream will come true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
This was assured by the group&#39;s bassist and co-founder Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on the South American leg of their 20th anniversary tour and on Sunday 20th they will be making their only stop in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30pm along with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You read an excerpt of the conversation, a full transcript of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
A dream comes true for your Costa Rican fans when Pearl Jam plays Costa Rica: do you realize what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is also coming true for us.
This is just the second time we&#39;ve played in South and Central America and so far it&#39;s been great.
I&#39;ve only been to Costa Rica once for vacation. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It&#39;s exciting for us to take our music there.
I&#39;m asking you this because the fans are totally devoted to the band. They experience the days before the concert very intensively.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to come to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry it took so long to get here.
Some people even think your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn&#39;t that put a bit of pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we&#39;ve put on in the last 21 years have happened in the last two weeks.
We played some big shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that got us ready for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we feel like playing there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are enthusiastic about the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world for this.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are just amazing.
My friends used to go to Costa Rica and Nicaragua to surf. Along with Mexico, these are great areas for surfing. That&#39;s how, through people who love surfing, we found out about it.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the Costa Rica event?
Since we&#39;ve never played there before, we don&#39;t set ourselves any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with a lot of different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and varied repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that&#39;s partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so deciding which one to play isn&#39;t easy.
Adding two or three songs to our repertoire that we haven&#39;t played in a while helps us keep our focus and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked those songs. Otherwise they might be forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think therefore also for the audience.
With this tour you are celebrating your twenty year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yes totally.
First of all, I don&#39;t think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years. That looks like a dream.
We continue to rely on this blessing and think it&#39;s great that we can still make music together.
We like each other and are passionate about making music.
We&#39;re lucky to be able to go to places in the world we&#39;ve always wanted to visit.
Things couldn&#39;t be better.
What did it mean to you to have actively participated in the birth of grunge?
It&#39;s always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We&#39;re good friends with the folks at Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and rather unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Once in a while a band will come out of a town, but it&#39;s unusual for five or ten groups to come out of the same town at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We&#39;re happy to still be friends with all of them and honored to be a part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It&#39;s also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is a lot more time than many bands last.
First of all, I think we all consider ourselves lucky to be alive and besides, we care for each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical avenues have opened up, giving each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and their music. We couldn&#39;t be better off.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we&#39;ve grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to tour too often because it&#39;s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds loving your music.
As long as you remember that people came for the music, it reminds you that you need to respect the music and what brought it to life without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We were never interested in that anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed that it took so long. We&#39;re still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who helped us build the band. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
Local band Las Robertas are responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that&#39;s why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band the best. That&#39;s why we&#39;re curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. That will definitely be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That&#39;s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to mind.
Who were your influences as a bass player?
From so many+
First ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could spend the afternoon talking about the bass players I like.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge alive when it&#39;s no longer a fad?
I think we all don&#39;t feel very connected to the word grunge.
Thinking about it, I can think of the bands I mentioned earlier like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they&#39;re still relevant today, I think that&#39;s great because this music is worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever.
Initially their music was darker, now it&#39;s more positive.
Why?
That&#39;s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that might seem a bit flippant. But there are other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
Both brought tears to my eyes when I heard Ed play them. They are very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - like losing a family member or a friend - it affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs definitely embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
