Fujimori went to the hospital again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was rushed to a public hospital on Tuesday to assess muscle loss in his legs, his family doctor said.
72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights abuses during his reign (1990-2000), has multiple ailments, including tongue cancer, which has undergone four surgeries and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal doctor, told TV that Fujimori would be examined for three days at Peru&#39;s Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas hospital to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that he thought Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds. Nevertheless, he did not wish this because he considered him innocent.
He has had four operations for tongue cancer and has lost 40 pounds. In addition, there are other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Since September 2007, Fujimori has been held in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía detention center.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the killing of 25 people by the Peruvian army&#39;s death squad, which operated clandestinely during his reign.
