Squat, where huge parties were held, was evacuated
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes Street (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without putting up any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of house number 51 on Calle Balmes have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they had illegally occupied and where they had organized huge parties that had driven the neighborhood to desperation at noon yesterday. The eviction was carried out by order of a judge without any police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was changed to avoid a similar situation.
&quot;From now on, access will be controlled,&quot; confirmed the property manager.
The squatters, who occupied 11 of the building&#39;s 13 apartments - the remainder were occupied - took away the entire electrical system and part of the water supply. They also painted the walls and left all kinds of rubbish, mostly cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were celebrated on the three lower floors, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business has dropped by 80% since the squat began.
The owner of the disco pointed out that the squatters were unfairly competing with her by selling the drinks for 3 euros, while in the discotheque they cost 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the leisure center had been reported by the neighbors for disturbing the peace, while according to her, the noise did not come from the visitors to the disco, but from the squatters and, in particular, from the guests of the parties that were organized there and who, according to the disgruntled neighbors have become more and longer in recent weeks.
The manager of the nightclub explained that the nuisance was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (municipal police) also confirmed that they had received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
The leader of the PP (Partido Popular - People&#39;s Party) in Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, last week called for the building to be vacated immediately and for the problems of civic coexistence and the dilapidation of the neighborhood to be tackled.
He explained that before the summer only one floor of the building was occupied, but that in recent months squatters have penetrated all floors of the building and almost all apartments. Some had even been stolen.
In this sense, he added that &quot;there is a need to end impunity and crack down on anti-social acts in the building.&quot;
Yesterday another building in the Nou Barris neighborhood was evacuated by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., police approached 35 Montral Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who saw four people trying to enter the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
park or mountain?
Apart from the arguments about the fees, the architects agree with the tender.
The municipal tender for the 16 Gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), that administration published its diatribe on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It has even been compared in numbers to New York&#39;s Central Park.
With the sinking of the CMB in 1987, in the eyes of many, the park once again became the upper limit of Barcelona, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in a north-south direction, but rather upwards (mountains) and downwards ( Sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park plays with this idea.
Central Park was no longer used as a model, but Yellowstone with wild boar in the role of the yogi bear.
That&#39;s how far things were when the city issued a huge tender consisting of 16 competitions for further access gates to Collserola in September.
Undoubtedly, a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that is so, or someone is planning to put gates on the land.
The question arises: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for proposals is the talking point on the lips of all architects from Barcelona, not only from an organizational point of view, but also in terms of reflecting on the city.
It&#39;s almost a recurrent subject for two members of this long-established caste who meet in the elevator to draw on.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the material for one of the rare coincidences between what three architects from Barcelona think about it and some university professors who applied to the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán, &quot;it is necessary&quot; after the attack on the coast to speak about the &quot;mountain front&quot;, as long as Ildefons Cerda&#39;s discourse on the green apples has not been carried out.
&quot;One should start from the principle that Barcelona&#39;s biggest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex,&quot; judges the architect, for whom the title &quot;Gates of Collserola&quot; harbors a &quot;lexical trap&quot;: They should not be &quot;imagined as entrances to a park, but as the delimitation of areas where trade takes place must.&quot;
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban planning experience, sees the proposal as an &quot;intellectual challenge&quot; that harbors &quot;some dangers&quot;.
Dangers as a result of the &quot;uncertainty that the design of a public space entails nowadays&quot; after the experiences from the 1980s, which had their &quot;swan song&quot; in the area of the forum.
The first fear is one&#39;s own limitation of what may be built on.
&quot;To limit something always means to determine the next step&quot;, ie to go beyond it.
&quot;You have to think about new urban planning tools because the current ones [referring to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM) ] can lead to a real catastrophe.&quot;
Modol, who follows the question more closely, believes, simply, that the side of Collserola that goes towards Vallesana &quot;can be understood as a park, that towards Barcelona cannot&quot;, for purely topographical reasons.
