He explained that the aim of the study is to understand the factors and the role of genetics linked to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of World Diabetes Day, he said the goal is for 3,000 children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 to complete nutritional questionnaires with parental consent and supervision.
You will also be asked questions about your level of physical activity and family history of the disease to control for risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He further explained that on the said Saturdays, subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), checked their blood pressure and blood parameters such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes linked to childhood obesity ) would be determined.
Cruz López stressed that the research was being carried out in response to health workers&#39; concerns about the alarming weight gain in young people.
&quot;The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years the proportion of obese boys had increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Overweight had also increased dramatically,&quot; emphasized the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that the average Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes linked to diabetes and obesity .
More generally, he explained that the genetics of obesity is an inability to burn the excess energy (calories) we eat, so that it is stored as fat.
