The high calorie intake, that is, increased consumption of sugar-sweetened beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) along with high fat and protein intake, and the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from the UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at Mexico&#39;s UNAM University, is developing polymer-modified asphalts to make the mix more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
Paying attention to the signs emanating from the pavement would not require repairing nearly 200,000 potholes when the rainy season hits the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (municipality of the Valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and affirming that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt pavement is done properly, the number of potholes will be significantly reduced or even avoided altogether.
In his presentation &quot;Potholes from a Technical Perspective&quot; given at the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with an extremely hot climate, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the pavement and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - called asphaltenes - and the other part has a low molecular weight - called malthenes. Together they give the road surface its characteristic tough-elastic behavior.
Viscous behavior of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
&quot;This means that the durability of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes over the course of a day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations,&quot; explained the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the majority of Mexico City&#39;s streets have flexible pavement made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include asphalt.
Between the top layers is a wearing course of asphalt, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then consolidated.
Every single stone of this wearing course has been bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the pavement.
&quot;If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be distributed even better,&quot; said the chemical engineer.
&quot;On top of the wearing course,&quot; he explained, &quot;a final layer is laid, called the base course, which is made up of tiny stones, ie sand that has also been bathed in asphalt.
Because this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require greater mechanical force than the wear layer and must create friction.
In addition, since this pavement receives and distributes most of the forces, the base course needs to be of adequate thickness and the material from which it is made needs to be maintained.
Weather conditions, particularly humidity and temperature variations, are other important factors to consider, above all water,&quot; he said, &quot;because it significantly affects the behavior of the wearing course.
When the terrain becomes wet, water seeps into the layer and has difficulty exiting. This causes softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is created,&quot; he said, &quot;the top layer is worn away first, and the wearing course is only degraded afterwards. But the damage is not instantaneous, it is a process that would need to be addressed through proper maintenance programs at the first sign.&quot;
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico&#39;s National Research System) explained that vehicle load is another important cause of pothole occurrence. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of road surface must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is followed in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and with which potholes can be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
