Such was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a lophoscopist from the Investigative Unit of the Prosecutor&#39;s Office (CTI) from Cali came in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot; by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in CTI&#39;s department, on call this week was Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has worked in criminal investigations for 21 years.
Early in his career, González worked in Chocó communities, where he often had to venture into the jungle for five days to reach the location of the bodies he was tasked with identifying.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, ie the palms and soles.
During the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big awaited him.
He flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca on Friday night.
He knew he was to identify two bodies, and there was a suspicion that one might be that of the man who had led the world&#39;s oldest guerrilla. Therefore, he should take Guillermo León Sáenz&#39;s tenfingerprint sheet (his real name) with him.
However, when he reached the place where the corpse was with the medical examination, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, which did not at all resemble the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don&#39;t lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a trowel, and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the corpse&#39;s fingerprints to those on the print sheet.
He had seen correctly: It was &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of telling the Secretary of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was in fact the head of the FARC.
In search of clues
For a dactyloscopist from Sijín in Cali, the tribute President Juan Manuel Santos gave Eliazar González at a press conference on the operation against &quot;Cano&quot; was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with zero margin of error that can be a key factor in solving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also assist in murder and robbery investigations and confirm the identities of those arrested.
When arrested, many criminals present false identification papers or do not have them.
We take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher told us that when he stole a piece of wall from a house, he had to rip it out because the thief had put his hand on that spot when he pulled out a safe stuffed with jewelry and money.
&quot;Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting. But in this case, we were able to take the whole handprint and identify the criminal who participated in several thefts,&quot; he recalled.
Fingerprints can also be used to exonerate or incriminate murder suspects.
A body was recently found surrounded by liquor bottles.
During the investigation, it was suspected that a family member could be a suspect, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
While this does not guarantee the killer is identified, it does link him to the location where the crime was committed.
A dactyloscopist at the CTI explained that &quot;fingerprints are taken from the object using chemical or physical reagents.&quot;
When they appear, a planting trowel or ribbon is used to take them away.
The fingerprints are then sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
&quot;The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers,&quot; explained the CTI expert.
He said that not everything is as it is portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as all that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you carry out a corresponding comparison.
