Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption, ending the free fall spiral from early March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that culminated in a nuclear crisis and the worst disaster Japan had experienced since World War II.
The Tokyo government&#39;s initial estimates put property damage at $300,000, a blow that appears to be slowing despite the troubled global economy.
After three quarters of falling, the July-September gross domestic product figures finally served to close this chapter: GDP grew by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at the annualized rate.
The figure for the second quarter - Japan&#39;s fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the fastest growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The rebound can be partially explained by the sale of machinery for rebuilding areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1% compared to the 0.9% drop for equity investments recorded from January to March, the first drop after six months of unstoppable increases.
Nevertheless, the actual turnaround in the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on Keynesian impulses that use the crisis to build or build new infrastructure.
Japan woke up thanks in particular to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, buoyed by growing spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has turned to the domestic market after the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the &quot;haven currencies&quot; for investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and bleak US outlook, a privilege that has become a tombstone in accounts the export company burdens.
With a harder currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious problem for a country whose economy relies on the health of the big tech producers.
Toyota and Sony, for example, attributed their weak July-September results to the yen&#39;s appreciation.
As markets continue to besiege peripheral EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government remains vigilant.
&quot;One has to be alert to the ongoing risks, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen,&quot; said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
