Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would intervene again in currency markets if the yen continues to appreciate.
&quot;Should we detect excessive volatility&quot; in the exchange rate of the yen, &quot;we will intervene as we did last time,&quot; M. Noda told the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen had recovered close to historic levels that forced Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31st.
On the day, Tokyo had sold the yen against the dollar massively in a bid to lower the Japanese currency value, which is about to hit a new high since 1945 against the dollar.
However, the yen has regularly risen above it, bolstered by buying from investors who view the yen as a &quot;safe haven&quot; during these uncertain times of global economic downturn and European debt crisis.
The dollar slipped below 77 yen on Tuesday, the euro slipped below the symbolic 105 yen bar, near the levels that triggered the last intervention.
Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This flash in the pan of Japanese currency is hurting the archipelago&#39;s exports by increasing the cost of &quot;Made in Japan&quot; products and reducing the income value drawn by Japanese companies from abroad as they convert them into local currency.
&quot;Japan is struggling to rebuild after the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region (northeast),&quot; stresses M. Noda, who fears that the yen&#39;s appreciation could kill the weak recovery in the bud.
The world&#39;s third economic powerhouse has regained traction for the first time this year, with growth in the third quarter of -1.5% compared to the previous quarter, thanks to the surge in exports and the consumption of households &quot;sealed&quot; by the disaster.
However, the Prime Minister estimates that the appreciation of the yen does not reflect &quot;Japan&#39;s economic fundamentals&quot;.
For his part, Finance Minister Jun Azumi has urged the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy committee on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
However, Hirohide Yamaguchi, deputy governor of the institute, has indicated that the BoJ has already taken &quot;appropriate measures&quot;, saying that no further currency easing is expected on Wednesday.
At its most recent meeting in late October, the central bank increased its government bond purchases by 5 trillion yen ($48 billion) to repay the 55 trillion yen (519 billion Euro) of collateral it had spent on various financial asset purchases to boost the liquidity market flood.
Euro zone:
Interest rates are skyrocketing, stock markets are retreating
The risk of contagion from the debt crisis is constantly undermining European indicators.
Despite the inauguration of the new heads of government in Greece and Italy and the best growth figures in France and Germany, the rates of the weakened countries continue to rise.
Stock markets, still worried about the stability of the Eurozone, drift a little more into negative territory this Tuesday, November 15th.
In Paris at 10 a.m., the CAC lost 1.4% and fell to 3,064 points.
The Dax in Frankfurt fell by 0.4%, London by 0.1%.
&quot;Global equity markets continue to shed some of their recent gains on renewed tensions over government bond yields in the troubled euro zone.
&quot;Investors are nervous and all too aware of the risk of contagion,&quot; said Terry Pratt, institutional broker at IG Markets, as quoted by Reuters.
The Tokyo Stock Exchange, which is suffering from renewed fears among European capacity market participants that the debt crisis will persist, closed down 0.7%.
&quot;Japan, like the rest of the world, has its eyes on Europe and trading will remain within a limited range of variation until investors have evidence that the situation has stabilised,&quot; estimates Mitsushige Akino, fund manager at Ichiyoshi Investment Management .
This resurgence of concerns about the future of the euro zone is hurting the single currency, which continued its bearish run into Tuesday.
The euro has been at its lowest level for a month and a half.
As of 10 am, the European currency was worth $1.3570, down 0.4%.
According to stockbrokers, it fell after the CDU, Chancellor Angela Merkel&#39;s party, which met in Congress on Monday, approved a motion that specifically provides for the possibility for troubled countries to leave the eurozone without simultaneously to leave the European Union.
The Italian and Spanish rates are well below the 6% mark.
Lending rates in Italy and Spain remain at very worrying levels.
This Tuesday morning, the yield on Italian 10-year bonds reached 6.85%, while that on Spanish bonds matured to 6.2%.
These tensions in interest rates in the southern countries, but also in France, continue to feed investors&#39; fears.
Future Italian Prime Minister Mario Monti called for more time for the markets to restore Italy&#39;s situation, which was threatened by paralysis from the debt burden.
For his part, the new Greek Prime Minister Lucas Papademos had confirmed that the implementation of the decisions taken at the October 27 euro zone summit was &quot;the main task&quot; of his government.
Spain is in the markets&#39; sights as the country&#39;s general elections take place on Sunday.
The interest rate gap (&quot;spread&quot;) between the German and Spanish 10-year bonds has once again reached a new, historic high.
In anticipation of Eurozone growth figures
Statistically, France posted household consumption-led economic growth of 0.4% in the third quarter, slightly better than the expected 0.3%.
However, the Federal Statistical Office INSEE had revised the bearish figures for the second quarter, namely with a minus of 0.1% of the gross domestic product (GDP) instead of stagnation.
In truth, it&#39;s the fourth quarter that worries economists the most.
Germany, for its part, recorded growth of 0.5% over the same period.
A first projection for the entire euro zone is expected at 11 a.m., with the EU Commission warning of the risk of a renewed recession.
energy policy:
Facts should triumph over dogma
If there is one topic that should not be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or because of emotions, it is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to use an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the full economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinions on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving the demand for electricity to double by 2050, lest an enormous proportion of the world&#39;s population be without a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to be able to continue producing electricity steadily, without forgetting the imperative to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
As a result, Germany remains isolated in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subjecting its decision to the need to find a substitute source that can be substituted, nor in Switzerland, which intends to build only last-generation nuclear power plants.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few countries, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
For its part, after Fukushima, the United States decided to add another unit to its park by reopening the Three Mile Island plant, which had been shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is geared towards renewable energy sources, is occasionally presented as a role model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will be reflected in the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increased dependency on Russia for energy due to the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
All of these unpleasant effects will become noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives food for thought.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in terms of wind energy, from which it gets 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the largest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill that is 40% higher than our French households.
Since the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness in the globalized economy and a guarantee of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore entail a sharp increase in the price of energy, making the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power illusory.
Polls have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay as they are to the principle of this source of energy.
Let&#39;s remember that our country&#39;s energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a plethora of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
Should France decide to phase out nuclear power, a large proportion of these SMEs would fall victim and the annual 6 billion euros in capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink further and further.
What electrician would hire an EPR designed to work for sixty years when its manufacturer&#39;s demise is inevitable?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that there is no such thing as a miracle cure for generating electricity, just as there is no devil&#39;s work.
The low-CO2 solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy bear witness to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security agency that carries out uncompromising and transparent controls in existing plants, such as the Flamanville building.
Their work teams, renowned for their professionalism, are obsessed with the idea of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
Only one, at Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions; it took place without any consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was conjured up by reactor design and inexcusable human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two unprecedented natural disasters that claimed the lives of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn lessons from this accident just as it did after the previous two.
The fruit of this approach, as well as a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a draft that allows it to withstand such phenomena.
Since building a nuclear power plant is considered desirable among electrical engineers, halting construction in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the Areva and EDF competitors, giving them free rein to usurp the leadership position in the inevitable nuclear power development.
It is imperative and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overburdening of police, judiciary and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a &quot;country of human rights&quot;, as France had dubbed itself.
Recently, official harassment of foreign students had dominated newsreels, with the interior minister casually announcing (see Libération May 23) that France &quot;does not need talent, masons or waiters from abroad&quot;.
But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus between the right and the left on this issue.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that &quot;900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million migrant workers, should not pose a problem for a country&quot;, on the left by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990, France &quot;could not absorb all the poverty in the world&quot;.
The only difference is the degree of generosity
Fear of invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared in 2005 by both right and left.
Both camps saw the immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is in the level of generosity one is willing to show towards immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande confines himself to banalities that point out that development based on partnership makes it possible to solve our &quot;migration problems&quot;.
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have electoral implications; however, it is economically expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent work summarizing the latest evidence on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.) , there is a broad consensus among specialists regarding the positive influence of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Restricting immigration would sap growth and damage the labor market situation.
Fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the local workforce, especially the lower-skilled ones, by putting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than native wage workers, as they tend to work in sectors that are underutilized.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that are unattractive to local wage workers, while the more skilled immigrants work in dynamic sectors where education is not matched with the labor supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity between natives and migrants also creates a positive effect of immigrant influx on wages and domestic labor markets.
Giovanni Peri calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the immigrant tide would produce an implied long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without considering the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants is conducive to idea generation and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net contribution to the social systems, averaging around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labor Organization estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 will on average make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over their lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the missing points of intersection &quot;with the teeth&quot; when he took up his mandate.
However, these said teeth, designed to deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity; also a sensitive commodity.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after their invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, wrote throughout the 20th century about the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the Supreme in Greece had endured.
Some might have believed that exercising the right to vote, and doing so in the most direct way possible, was enough to see democracy triumph over its enemies once and for all.
It has been known since Napoleon &quot;the little one&quot; that it was a question of a mental attitude.
Universal suffrage, which is a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become an &quot;instrument of oppression&quot;, as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social community spirit, a judiciary.
The crisis in Europe that we are going through is an economic crisis, but it is also, first and foremost, a political and democratic crisis.
The change of heart of the Greek true-false referendum would have been doubly revealing in this regard: that of the need for a vigorous return of politics, but also that of the disturbing sense of its impossibility, of its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered obsolete.
The truth is that the frontlines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and the Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by urging the success of the national referendum, which was organized according to necessity and in the wrong order.
A free pass for the European autocrat or a blindfolded leap into the void of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want a cleaver, but a collective task, with every right, calm and steady, an election and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - by the way, we don&#39;t know where to end the list - because there is only one crisis and it is in Europe.
It is all of Europe that is bowing to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is all of Europe that is humiliated on an international level.
There is concern about transfers of sovereignty towards Europe - when it is all of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each and every one of the nations that are part of it.
The urgency is to restore leadership of the European project to popular sovereignty.
Because it is up to the whole, whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debt, break free from the markets and build a future through investment.
Getting out of the crisis is conditional on decisions at European level, which cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, without certainty leading us to our doom.
Long opposed to this proposal by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, everyone is now pushing European economic leaders to do so.
Agreed.
But to imagine this without political integration and a stronger democracy - as citizens envision - would be yet another folly and dead end.
We must undertake a new stage in European construction.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to &quot;create&quot; republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not do enough here.
This instruction remains valid.
We need to build a more integrated Europe on an economic level.
This can only be achieved by creating a politically more democratic Europe, a truly European popular sovereignty.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
&quot;Contactless&quot; chip cards are becoming common property
The world trade fair for chip cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris with an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor chips (debit cards, SIM card telephones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment here is contactless technology, which makes it possible to pay for public transport or purchases simply by holding the card up to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards should be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share should continue to grow in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent over 10% of the global smart card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in contactless payment after long lagging behind Asia Pacific.
Some 26 million Visa cards already have this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless Visa cards have been distributed.
However, hypermarkets are making steam.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move to higher speeds, it is now necessary for banks to provide their customers with these cards.
&quot;Two major French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically issuing their customers with bank cards equipped with a contactless chip,&quot; announced Gérard Nebouy, General Manager of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing mobile payments
However, this is only the first step on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A tiny percentage of devices are currently equipped with the necessary NFC (Near Field Communication) technology to carry out these transactions.
&quot;You are in default&quot;.
&quot;But they should at least see some real improvement next year.&quot;
&quot;We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units worldwide in 2012,&quot; explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE runs a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also announced yesterday that it was preparing to launch an offer that would allow its customers to make contactless payments by cell phone.
Terrorist front, of course, from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about ties between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
