Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and directly connects Western Europe with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is designed to supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with pomp and splendor.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline on the Baltic Sea coast, to the sound of an orchestra and at a gourmet buffet, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically turned the control of the valve that feeds Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through an initial 1,224 km pipeline connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-West Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which will allow a total delivery of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of all France&#39;s consumption - is due to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the possibility of building a third line on the same route is already being hinted at.
For Gazprom, the timely and on-time completion of this enormous structure looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
In fact, the Nord Stream pipeline will enable gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any routing through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
Because of this, these two countries are losing a little of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to shut it off from Western European markets.
Warsaw, most involved in the debate, had not shied away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline to a &quot;new German-Soviet pact&quot; linked to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is extremely sensitive politically.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the approval of this Russian project.
However, this is at the cost of weakening European energy, since the project has created a breach between western and eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to impose its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-consuming and dwindling Western countries.
&quot;This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way&quot;, confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the large gas contracts are also political and economic aspects are important.
All this explains the broad smiles of the many Gazprom managers in Lubmin regarding the gas pipeline.
The construction of this long-distance gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel with a concrete coating to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed at a depth of about 200 m.
During its construction, minefields dating back to the Second World War had to be avoided.
&quot;Around hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,&quot; said Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream company.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is uninterrupted along its entire length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was envisaged off the coast of Sweden, but those responsible for the project refrained from doing so because the Swedes were not very keen on seeing a Russian state company settling off their shores on a permanent basis.
&quot;In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute,&quot; specified Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the long-distance gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, since the welds were estimated to resist a leak of one per 100,000 years.
State surveillance of the gas pipeline is provided both by an underwater robot controlled from a seagoing vessel for external observation purposes and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
Shaped like a cigar, one meter in diameter, it is inserted inside the pipe and propelled by the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the pipeline at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device, upon arrival, provides the most accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without requiring even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point and 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The German companies E.ON and BASF are also affiliated here (each with 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group of companies GDF Suez (each with 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom then leased the company&#39;s entire gas transmission capacity under a 20-year renewable contract.
&quot;Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,&quot; specified Jens Muller.
The financing of the long-distance gas pipeline construction was secured 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labor costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the total investment was 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are confident that they will recover their expenses since Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The long-distance gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-forested stretch of coast near Lubmin.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet port.
