Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Launched by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to bring a new style to writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black square cover, elastic strap, off-white pages, as if aged with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to bring a distinguished design notebook onto the market.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company&#39;s consultant, is in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton varnish used, for example, for upholstered benches.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
&quot;Moleskine has revived an ancient and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,&quot; explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first few years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create an identikit of buyers because the notebook appeals to business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which started out with 12 employees, now has over 100 employees and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on websites like Fnac, in small boutiques in city centers and knows how to assert its identity.
&quot;We have followed the zeitgeist and its new need for writing, despite the rise of email,&quot; explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the Moleskine company: recently the brand launched an exposition called &quot;Detour (detour) &quot; in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard print cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and knew how to diversify its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer sleeves... The brand has the full range of items.
A success that brings envious people to the scene: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today&#39;s Syntegra Capital, thus opening a new chapter in the history of the Moleskine company.
Why does unemployment among disabled workers remain so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The &quot;15th week of work for the disabled&quot; begins today.
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% unemployment for the entire population.
Daunting?
&quot;No,&quot; says Éric Blanchet, director general of the Adapt association, which organizes the &quot;Week of work for the disabled&quot;.
&quot;The progress made in fifteen years is significant.&quot;
&quot;Back then, the unemployment rate wasn&#39;t twice, it was three times as high.&quot;
&quot;Nevertheless, there is still a lot to do.&quot;
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they can get a job.
It affects the elderly more often: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have low levels of qualifications: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% among the disabled versus 38% overall.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the workforce and that &quot;is at the heart of the problem,&quot; according to Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
What remains is the unspoken, the attitudes that are certainly, but slowly, evolving.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for La Cité magazine said the managers surveyed had &quot;a low level of knowledge about the disabled&quot; that was &quot;overrepresented by people in wheelchairs, the mentally or intellectually disabled&quot;.
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to meet the employment target of 6% disabled workforce set out in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, which are from 2008, refer to a quotient of 2.6%.
&quot;We&#39;re now at around 3%,&quot; says Pierre Blanc, general director of Agefiph, the organization charged with collecting contributions from companies that don&#39;t comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of &quot;fee-paying&quot; establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the amounts paid in, between 2007 and 2011, numerically from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
&quot;The law of 2005, which provides for increases in contributions, put a lot of pressure on companies, explained Pierre Blanc.&quot;
&quot;But this improvement also expresses a real realization, particularly in the large corporate groups.&quot;
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments with between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
Hazard: &quot;What luck&quot;
Even before they faced the &quot;blue Tuesday evenings&quot; (8:45 p.m.), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens had not hidden the pleasure that the friendly brought them.
It would be going too far to say that there was a collusion between them, but the picture speaks symbolic volumes.
Sitting side by side on the spectator podium at the Stade de France, George Leekens and Eden Hazard could well have made peace.
Five months after his forward&#39;s spirited gesture against Turkey, the Belgium coach had received nothing but personal praise.
&quot;I am very happy with Eden, his progress and the fact that he is Belgian&quot;.
&quot;I want to look ahead,&quot; assures the native of Liller.
As for the contrast between his portrayal at club and national level: &quot;It&#39;s a unit, that justifies everything.&quot;
&quot;I&#39;m in Lille all year round, which isn&#39;t the case in Belgium&quot;.
&quot;It&#39;s time for me to start&quot;.
Hazard will come to Saint-Denis, brought on Friday night against Romania for the match against France, to finally &quot;shine&quot;.
