For his part, Leekens tossed &quot;pride&quot; with good nature.
&quot;The Pride of Hosting a Gala Match&quot;.
&quot;Proud&quot; also to confirm - in his capacity as &quot;neighbours&quot; - that France &quot;have again become a team at a very high level&quot;, a little more than a year after the Knysna trauma.
&quot;Laurent Blanc did a damn good job,&quot; he said enthusiastically.
Although Belgium will be absent from the next European Championship, the technician sees himself sharing the plane with the Blues (the French national team)... bound for Brazil in 2014.
&quot;We little Belgians make it big,&quot; he said.
&quot;We are planning something, the players are ambitious, they are hungry.&quot;
&quot;You&#39;ll notice that in the upcoming games.&quot; The game against France included.
Portugal very confident
Paulo Bento&#39;s Portuguese team is looking forward to the second leg against Bosnia (10:00 p.m.) this Tuesday in Lisbon with great optimism.
In the first leg, both teams lacked objectivity.
&quot;At the end of these 90 minutes we will be a happy team and above all a happy country.&quot;
Paulo Bento already sees himself in Poland and Ukraine.
He has not the slightest doubt that &quot;La Selecçao&quot;, his national team, for which he has been responsible since September 2010, will qualify for the 2012 European Championship.
Indeed, for Portugal, that means just 90 minutes of bliss.
But there is a match to play and an opponent to sack, and that is Bosnia.
Considering Friday&#39;s first leg (0-0) in the Hell of Zenica, it seems obvious that the die is not yet cast.
Portugal dominated the game for more than an hour, but the side were unable to put the all-important stamp on the game to take the pressure off.
&quot;It&#39;s a good result, but it comes with a certain risk as we didn&#39;t score an away goal.&quot;
At home, however, in their brightly lit Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are confident they can pull through in front of a crowd that is bound to be just as keen to see the game, even though the game was of course announced as &#39;very close&#39;, he said the optimistic but clear-eyed Bento.
&quot;We&#39;re expecting a very close match but we&#39;re fully confident that we can prevail,&quot; said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
&quot;We still have a 50% chance of being part of the 2012 European Championships,&quot; said Carlos Queiroz&#39;s successor.
Friday&#39;s draw in Bosnia will force the Portuguese to score and win.
